events.description: Heartbroken by the deaths of her sons Nero and Drusus, and banished to the island of Pandateria by Tiberius, Agrippina the Elder dies of self-inflicted starvation.
events.html: • 33 – Heartbroken by the deaths of her sons Nero and Drusus, and banished to the island of Pandateria by Tiberius, Agrippina the Elder dies of self-inflicted starvation.[1]

events.description: Pappus of Alexandria, Greek philosopher, observes an eclipse of the Sun and writes a commentary on The Great Astronomer (Almagest).
events.html: • 320 – Pappus of Alexandria, Greek philosopher, observes an eclipse of the Sun and writes a commentary on The Great Astronomer (Almagest).

events.description: King Chlothar II promulgates the Edict of Paris (Edictum Chlotacharii), a sort of Frankish Magna Carta that defends the rights of the Frankish nobles while it excludes Jews from all civil employment in the Frankish Kingdom.
events.html: • 614 – King Chlothar II promulgates the Edict of Paris (Edictum Chlotacharii), a sort of Frankish Magna Carta that defends the rights of the Frankish nobles while it excludes Jews from all civil employment in the Frankish Kingdom.

events.description: Dagobert I is crowned King of the Franks.
events.html: • 629 – Dagobert I is crowned King of the Franks.

events.description: The Church of the Holy Sepulchre, a Christian church in Jerusalem, is completely destroyed by the Fatimid caliph Al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah, who hacks the Church's foundations down to bedrock.
events.html: • 1009 – The Church of the Holy Sepulchre, a Christian church in Jerusalem, is completely destroyed by the Fatimid caliph Al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah, who hacks the Church's foundations down to bedrock.

events.description: The Danes defeat the English in the Battle of Assandun.
events.html: • 1016 – The Danes defeat the English in the Battle of Assandun.

events.description: The Normans defeat the Byzantine Empire in the Battle of Dyrrhachium.
events.html: • 1081 – The Normans defeat the Byzantine Empire in the Battle of Dyrrhachium.

events.description: Pope Martin IV excommunicates King Peter III of Aragon for usurping the crown of Sicily (a sentence renewed on 7 May and 18 November 1282).
events.html: • 1281 – Pope Martin IV excommunicates King Peter III of Aragon[2] for usurping the crown of Sicily (a sentence renewed on 7 May and 18 November 1282).[3]

events.description: Basel earthquake, the most significant historic seismological event north of the Alps, destroys the town of Basel, Switzerland.
events.html: • 1356 – Basel earthquake, the most significant historic seismological event north of the Alps, destroys the town of Basel, Switzerland.

events.description: Spanish conquistador Hernando de Soto's forces destroy the fortified town of Mabila in present-day Alabama, killing Tuskaloosa.
events.html: • 1540 – Spanish conquistador Hernando de Soto's forces destroy the fortified town of Mabila in present-day Alabama, killing Tuskaloosa.

events.description: In Japan the fourth Battle of Kawanakajima is fought between the forces of Uesugi Kenshin and Takeda Shingen, resulting in a draw.
events.html: • 1561 – In Japan the fourth Battle of Kawanakajima is fought between the forces of Uesugi Kenshin and Takeda Shingen, resulting in a draw.

events.description: Ships belonging to the Matsura clan of Japan fail to capture the Portuguese trading carrack in the Battle of Fukuda Bay, the first recorded naval battle between Japan and the West.
events.html: • 1565 – Ships belonging to the Matsura clan of Japan fail to capture the Portuguese trading carrack in the Battle of Fukuda Bay, the first recorded naval battle between Japan and the West.

events.description: King Philip II of Spain sends his third and final armada against England, but it ends in failure due to storms. The remaining ships are captured or sunk by the English.
events.html: • 1597 – King Philip II of Spain sends his third and final armada against England, but it ends in failure due to storms. The remaining ships are captured or sunk by the English.[4]

events.description: Michael the Brave, Prince of Wallachia, defeats the Army of Andrew Báthory in the Battle of Șelimbăr, leading to the first recorded unification of the Romanian people.
events.html: • 1599 – Michael the Brave, Prince of Wallachia, defeats the Army of Andrew Báthory in the Battle of Șelimbăr, leading to the first recorded unification of the Romanian people.

events.description: Frendraught Castle in Scotland, the home of James Crichton of Frendraught, burns down.
events.html: • 1630 – Frendraught Castle in Scotland, the home of James Crichton of Frendraught, burns down.[5]

events.description: Boston shoemakers form the first American labor organization.
events.html: • 1648 – Boston shoemakers form the first American labor organization.

events.description: Signing of the Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle ends the War of the Austrian Succession.
events.html: • 1748 – Signing of the Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle ends the War of the Austrian Succession.

events.description: African-American poet Phillis Wheatley is freed from slavery.
events.html: • 1775 – African-American poet Phillis Wheatley is freed from slavery.

events.description: American Revolutionary War: The Burning of Falmouth (now Portland, Maine).
events.html: • 1775 – American Revolutionary War: The Burning of Falmouth (now Portland, Maine).

events.description: American Revolutionary War: The Franco-American Siege of Savannah is lifted.
events.html: • 1779 – American Revolutionary War: The Franco-American Siege of Savannah is lifted.

events.description: Treaty of Campo Formio is signed between France and Austria
events.html: • 1797 – Treaty of Campo Formio is signed between France and Austria

events.description: Herman Melville's Moby-Dick is first published as The Whale by Richard Bentley of London.
events.html: • 1851 – Herman Melville's Moby-Dick is first published as The Whale by Richard Bentley of London.

events.description: The Second Opium War finally ends at the Convention of Peking with the ratification of the Treaty of Tientsin, an unequal treaty.
events.html: • 1860 – The Second Opium War finally ends at the Convention of Peking with the ratification of the Treaty of Tientsin, an unequal treaty.

events.description: United States takes possession of Alaska after purchasing it from Russia for $7.2 million. Celebrated annually in the state as Alaska Day.
events.html: • 1867 – United States takes possession of Alaska after purchasing it from Russia for $7.2 million. Celebrated annually in the state as Alaska Day.

events.description: The United States takes possession of Puerto Rico from Spain.
events.html: • 1898 – The United States takes possession of Puerto Rico from Spain.

events.description: Count Bernhard von Bülow becomes chancellor of Germany.
events.html: • 1900 – Count Bernhard von Bülow becomes chancellor of Germany.[6]

events.description: First Balkan War: King Peter I of Serbia issues a declaration "To the Serbian People", as his country joins the war.
events.html: • 1912 – First Balkan War: King Peter I of Serbia issues a declaration "To the Serbian People", as his country joins the war.

events.description: The Schoenstatt Apostolic Movement is founded in Germany.
events.html: • 1914 – The Schoenstatt Apostolic Movement is founded in Germany.

events.description: The Crimean Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic is formed as part of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic.
events.html: • 1921 – The Crimean Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic is formed as part of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic.

events.description: The British Broadcasting Company (later Corporation)  is founded by a consortium, to establish a nationwide network of radio transmitters to provide a national broadcasting service.
events.html: • 1922 – The British Broadcasting Company (later Corporation) is founded by a consortium, to establish a nationwide network of radio transmitters to provide a national broadcasting service.

events.description: The Judicial Committee of the Privy Council overrules the Supreme Court of Canada in Edwards v. Canada when it declares that women are considered "Persons" under Canadian law.
events.html: • 1929 – The Judicial Committee of the Privy Council overrules the Supreme Court of Canada in Edwards v. Canada when it declares that women are considered "Persons" under Canadian law.

events.description: World War II: Soviet Union begins the liberation of Czechoslovakia from Nazi Germany.
events.html: • 1944 – World War II: Soviet Union begins the liberation of Czechoslovakia from Nazi Germany.

events.description: World War II: The state funeral of Field Marshal Erwin Rommel takes place in Ulm, Germany.
events.html: • 1944 – World War II: The state funeral of Field Marshal Erwin Rommel takes place in Ulm, Germany.

events.description: The USSR's nuclear program receives plans for the United States plutonium bomb from Klaus Fuchs at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
events.html: • 1945 – The USSR's nuclear program receives plans for the United States plutonium bomb from Klaus Fuchs at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.

events.description: A group of the Venezuelan Armed Forces, led by Mario Vargas, Marcos Pérez Jiménez and Carlos Delgado Chalbaud, stages a coup d'état against president Isaías Medina Angarita, who is overthrown by the end of the day.
events.html: • 1945 – A group of the Venezuelan Armed Forces, led by Mario Vargas, Marcos Pérez Jiménez and Carlos Delgado Chalbaud, stages a coup d'état against president Isaías Medina Angarita, who is overthrown by the end of the day.

events.description: Argentine military officer and politician Juan Perón marries actress Eva Duarte.
events.html: • 1945 – Argentine military officer and politician Juan Perón marries actress Eva Duarte.

events.description: Texas Instruments announces the Regency TR-1, the first mass-produced transistor radio.
events.html: • 1954 – Texas Instruments announces the Regency TR-1, the first mass-produced transistor radio.

events.description: Félicette, a black and white female Parisian stray cat, becomes the first cat launched into space.
events.html: • 1963 – Félicette, a black and white female Parisian stray cat, becomes the first cat launched into space.

events.description: The Soviet probe Venera 4 reaches Venus and becomes the first spacecraft to measure the atmosphere of another planet.
events.html: • 1967 – The Soviet probe Venera 4 reaches Venus and becomes the first spacecraft to measure the atmosphere of another planet.

events.description: German Autumn: A set of events revolving around the kidnapping of Hanns Martin Schleyer and the hijacking of a Lufthansa flight by the Red Army Faction (RAF) comes to an end when Schleyer is murdered and various RAF members allegedly commit suicide.
events.html: • 1977 – German Autumn: A set of events revolving around the kidnapping of Hanns Martin Schleyer and the hijacking of a Lufthansa flight by the Red Army Faction (RAF) comes to an end when Schleyer is murdered and various RAF members allegedly commit suicide.

events.html: • 1979 – The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) begins allowing people to have home satellite earth stations without a federal government license.

events.description: The Space Shuttle Atlantis launches on STS-34 to deploy the Jupiter-bound Galileo space probe.
events.html: • 1989 – The Space Shuttle Atlantis launches on STS-34 to deploy the Jupiter-bound Galileo space probe.[10]

events.description: The Supreme Council of Azerbaijan adopts a declaration of independence from the Soviet Union.
events.html: • 1991 – The Supreme Council of Azerbaijan adopts a declaration of independence from the Soviet Union.

events.description: Merpati Nustantara Airlines Flight 5601 crashes into Mount Papandayan near the town of Garut in West Java, Indonesia, killing 31.
events.html: • 1992 – Merpati Nustantara Airlines Flight 5601 crashes into Mount Papandayan near the town of Garut in West Java, Indonesia, killing 31.[11]

events.html: • 2003 – Bolivian gas conflict: Bolivian President Gonzalo Sánchez de Lozada is forced to resign and leave Bolivia.
